# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rocket-rust
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rocket-rust/request-response] In computer science, **request–response** or **request–reply** is one of the basic methods computers use to communicate with each other in a network, in which the first computer sends a *request* for some data and the second *responds* to the request.
[src:rocket-rust/request-response] More specifically, it is a message exchange pattern in which a requestor sends a request message to a replier system, which receives and processes the request, ultimately returning a message in response.
[src:rocket-rust/request-response] It is analogous to a telephone call, in which the caller must wait for the recipient to pick up before anything can be discussed.
[src:rocket-rust/request-response] This is a simple but powerful messaging pattern which allows two applications to have a two-way conversation with one another over a channel; it is especially common in client–server architectures.
[src:rocket-rust/request-response] Request–response pattern can be implemented synchronously (such as web service calls over HTTP) or asynchronously.
[src:rocket-rust/request-response] In contrast, **one-way** computer communication, which is like the push-to-talk or "barge in" feature found on some phones and two-way radios, sends a message without waiting for a response.
[src:rocket-rust/request-response] Sending an email is an example of one-way communication, and another example are fieldbus sensors, such as most CAN bus sensors, which periodically and autonomously send out their data, whether or not any other devices on the bus are listening for it.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] In packet switching networks, routing is the higher-level decision-making that directs network packets from their source toward their destination through intermediate network nodes by specific packet forwarding mechanisms.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Packet forwarding is the transit of network packets from one network interface to another.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Intermediate nodes are typically network hardware devices such as routers, gateways, firewalls, or switches.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] General-purpose computers also forward packets and perform routing, although they have no specially optimized hardware for the task.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] The routing process usually directs forwarding on the basis of routing tables.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Routing tables maintain a record of the routes to various network destinations.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Routing tables may be specified by an administrator, learned by observing network traffic or built with the assistance of routing protocols.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Routing, in a narrower sense of the term, often refers to IP routing and is contrasted with bridging.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] IP routing assumes that network addresses are structured and that similar addresses imply proximity within the network.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Structured addresses allow a single routing table entry to represent the route to a group of devices.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] In large networks, structured addressing (routing, in the narrow sense) outperforms unstructured addressing (bridging).
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Routing has become the dominant form of addressing on the Internet.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Bridging is still widely used within local area networks.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Unicast is the dominant form of message delivery on the Internet.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] This article focuses on unicast routing algorithms.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] With static routing, small networks may use manually configured routing tables.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Larger networks have complex topologies that can change rapidly, making the manual construction of routing tables unfeasible.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Nevertheless, most of the public switched telephone network (PSTN) uses pre-computed routing tables, with fallback routes if the most direct route becomes blocked (see routing in the PSTN).
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Dynamic routing attempts to solve this problem by constructing routing tables automatically, based on information carried by routing protocols, allowing the network to act nearly autonomously in avoiding network failures and blockages.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Examples of dynamic-routing protocols and algorithms include Routing Information Protocol (RIP), Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) and Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP).
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Distance vector algorithms use the Bellman–Ford algorithm.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] This approach assigns a *cost* number to each of the links between each node in the network.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Nodes send information from point A to point B via the path that results in the lowest *total cost* (i.e., the sum of the costs of the links between the nodes used).
[src:rocket-rust/routing] When a node first starts, it only knows of its immediate neighbors and the direct cost involved in reaching them.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] The neighboring nodes examine this information and compare it to what they already know; anything that represents an improvement on what they already have, they insert in their own table.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Over time, all the nodes in the network discover the best next hop and total cost for all destinations.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] When a network node goes down, any nodes that used it as their next hop discard the entry and convey the updated routing information to all adjacent nodes, which in turn repeat the process.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Eventually, all the nodes in the network receive the updates and discover new paths to all the destinations that do not involve the down node.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] When applying link-state algorithms, a graphical map of the network is the fundamental data used for each node.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] To produce its map, each node floods the entire network with information about the other nodes it can connect to.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Each node then independently assembles this information into a map.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Using this map, each router independently determines the least-cost path from itself to every other node using a standard shortest paths algorithm such as Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] The result is a tree graph rooted at the current node, such that the path through the tree from the root to any other node is the least-cost path to that node.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] This tree then serves to construct the routing table, which specifies the best next hop to get from the current node to any other node.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] A link-state routing algorithm optimized for mobile ad hoc networks is the optimized Link State Routing Protocol (OLSR).
[src:rocket-rust/routing] OLSR is proactive; it uses Hello and Topology Control (TC) messages to discover and disseminate link-state information through the mobile ad hoc network.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Using Hello messages, each node discovers 2-hop neighbor information and elects a set of *multipoint relays* (MPRs).
[src:rocket-rust/routing] MPRs distinguish OLSR from other link-state routing protocols.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Distance vector and link-state routing are both intra-domain routing protocols.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] They are used inside an autonomous system, but not between autonomous systems.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Both of these routing protocols become intractable in large networks and cannot be used in inter-domain routing.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Distance vector routing is subject to instability if there are more than a few hops in the domain.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Link-state routing needs significant resources to calculate routing tables.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] It also creates heavy traffic due to flooding.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Path-vector routing is used for inter-domain routing.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] It is similar to distance vector routing.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Path-vector routing assumes that one node (there can be many) in each autonomous system acts on behalf of the entire autonomous system.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] This node is called the *speaker node.* The speaker node creates a routing table and advertises it to neighboring speaker nodes in neighboring autonomous systems.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] The idea is the same as distance vector routing, except that only speaker nodes in each autonomous system can communicate with each other.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] The speaker node advertises the path, not the metric, of the nodes in its autonomous system or other autonomous systems.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] The path-vector routing algorithm is similar to the distance vector algorithm in the sense that each border router advertises the destinations it can reach to its neighboring router.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] However, instead of advertising networks in terms of a destination and the distance to that destination, networks are advertised as destination addresses and path descriptions to reach those destinations.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] The path, expressed in terms of the domains (or confederations) traversed so far, is carried in a special path attribute that records the sequence of routing domains through which the reachability information has passed.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] A route is defined as a pairing between a destination and the attributes of the path to that destination, thus the name, path-vector routing.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] The routers receive a vector that contains paths to a set of destinations.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Path selection involves applying a routing metric to multiple routes to select (or predict) the best route.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Most routing algorithms use only one network path at a time.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Multipath routing and specifically equal-cost multi-path routing techniques enable the use of multiple alternative paths.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] In computer networking, the metric is computed by a routing algorithm, and can cover information such as bandwidth, network delay, hop count, path cost, load, maximum transmission unit, reliability, and communication cost.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] The routing table stores only the best possible routes, while link-state or topological databases may store all other information as well.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] *Metric*: When comparing routes learned via the same routing protocol, a lower metric is preferred.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Metrics cannot be compared between routes learned from different routing protocols.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] *Administrative distance*: When comparing route table entries from different sources, such as different routing protocols and static configuration, a lower administrative distance indicates a more reliable source and thus a preferred route.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Because a routing metric is specific to a given routing protocol, multi-protocol routers must use some external heuristic to select between routes learned from different routing protocols.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Cisco routers, for example, attribute a value known as the administrative distance to each route, where smaller administrative distances indicate routes learned from a protocol assumed to be more reliable.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] A local administrator can set up host-specific routes that provide more control over network usage, permit testing, and better overall security.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] This is useful for debugging network connections or routing tables.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] In some small systems, a single central device decides ahead of time the complete path of every packet.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] In some other small systems, whichever edge device injects a packet into the network decides ahead of time the complete path of that particular packet.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] In either case, the route-planning device needs to know a lot of information about what devices are connected to the network and how they are connected to each other.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Once it has this information, it can use an algorithm such as A* search algorithm to find the best path.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] In high-speed systems, there are so many packets transmitted every second that it is infeasible for a single device to calculate the complete path for each and every packet.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Early high-speed systems dealt with this with circuit switching by setting up a path once for the first packet between some source and some destination; later packets between that same source and that same destination continue to follow the same path without recalculating until the circuit teardown.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Later high-speed systems inject packets into the network without any one device ever calculating a complete path for packets.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] In large systems, there are so many connections between devices, and those connections change so frequently, that it is infeasible for any one device to even know how all the devices are connected to each other, much less calculate a complete path through them.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Such systems generally use next-hop routing.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Most systems use a deterministic dynamic routing algorithm.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] When a device chooses a path to a particular final destination, that device always chooses the same path to that destination until it receives information that makes it think some other path is better.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] A few routing algorithms do not use a deterministic algorithm to find the best link for a packet to get from its original source to its final destination.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Instead, to avoid congestion hot spots in packet systems, a few algorithms use a randomized algorithm—Valiant's paradigm—that routes a path to a randomly picked intermediate destination, and from there to its true final destination.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] In many early telephone switches, a randomizer was often used to select the start of a path through a multistage switching fabric.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Depending on the application for which path selection is performed, different metrics can be used.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] For example, for web requests, one can use minimum latency paths to minimize web page load time, or for bulk data transfers, one can choose the least utilized path to balance load across the network and increase throughput.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] A popular path selection objective is to reduce the average completion times of traffic flows and the total network bandwidth consumption.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Recently, a path selection metric was proposed that computes the total number of bytes scheduled on the edges per path as a selection metric.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] An empirical analysis of several path selection metrics, including this new proposal, has been made available.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] In some networks, routing is complicated by the fact that no single entity is responsible for selecting paths; instead, multiple entities are involved in selecting paths or even parts of a single path.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Complications or inefficiency can result if these entities choose paths to optimize their own objectives, which may conflict with the objectives of other participants.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] A classic example involves traffic in a road system, in which each driver picks a path that minimizes their travel time.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] With such routing, the equilibrium routes can be longer than optimal for all drivers.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] In particular, Braess's paradox shows that adding a new road can *lengthen* travel times for all drivers.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] In a single-agent model used, for example, for routing automated guided vehicles (AGVs) on a terminal, reservations are made for each vehicle to prevent simultaneous use of the same part of an infrastructure.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] This approach is also referred to as context-aware routing.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] The Internet is partitioned into autonomous systems (ASs) such as internet service providers (ISPs), each of which controls routes involving its network.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] First, AS-level paths are selected via the BGP protocol that produces a sequence of ASs through which packets flow.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Each AS may have multiple paths, offered by neighboring ASs, from which to choose.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] These routing decisions often correlate with business relationships with these neighboring ASs, which may be unrelated to path quality or latency.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Second, once an AS-level path has been selected, there are often multiple corresponding router-level paths to choose from.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] This is due, in part, because two ISPs may be connected through multiple connections.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] In choosing the single router-level path, it is common practice for each ISP to employ hot-potato routing: sending traffic along the path that minimizes the distance through the ISP's own network—even if that path lengthens the total distance to the destination.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] For example, consider two ISPs, *A* and *B*.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Each has a presence in New York, connected by a fast link with latency 5 ms—and each has a presence in London connected by a 5 ms link.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Suppose both ISPs have trans-Atlantic links that connect their two networks, but *A*'s link has latency 100 ms and *B*'s has latency 120 ms.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] When routing a message from a source in *A*'s London network to a destination in *B*'s New York network, *A* may choose to immediately send the message to *B* in London.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] This saves *A* the work of sending it along an expensive trans-Atlantic link, but causes the message to experience latency 125 ms when the other route would have been 20 ms faster.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Additionally, a similar routing challenge can be observed in cellular networks, where different packets are destined for various endpoints, and each link exhibits varying spectral efficiency.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] In this context, the selection of the *optimal* path involves considering latency and packet error rate.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] To address this, multiple independent entities, one for each base station, play a crucial role in path selection while striving to optimize overall network performance.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] A 2003 measurement study of Internet routes found that, between pairs of neighboring ISPs, more than 30% of paths have inflated latency due to hot-potato routing, with 5% of paths being delayed by at least 12 ms.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Inflation due to AS-level path selection, while substantial, was attributed primarily to BGP's lack of a mechanism to directly optimize for latency, rather than to selfish routing policies.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] It was also suggested that, were an appropriate mechanism in place, ISPs would be willing to cooperate to reduce latency rather than use hot-potato routing.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Such a mechanism was later published by the same authors, first for the case of two ISPs and then for the global case.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] As the Internet and IP networks have become mission critical business tools, there has been increased interest in techniques and methods to monitor the routing posture of networks.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Incorrect routing or routing issues cause undesirable performance degradation, flapping or downtime.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Monitoring routing in a network is achieved using route analytics tools and techniques.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] In networks where a logically centralized control is available over the forwarding state, for example, using software-defined networking, routing techniques can be used that aim to optimize global and network-wide performance metrics.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] This has been used by large internet companies that operate many data centers in different geographical locations attached using private optical links, examples of which include Microsoft's Global WAN, Facebook's Express Backbone, and Google's B4.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Global performance metrics to optimize include maximizing network utilization, minimizing traffic flow completion times, maximizing the traffic delivered prior to specific deadlines and reducing the completion times of flows.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] Work on the later over private WAN discusses modeling routing as a graph optimization problem by pushing all the queuing to the end-points.
[src:rocket-rust/routing] The authors also propose a heuristic to solve the problem efficiently while sacrificing negligible performance.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:rocket-rust/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
